    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor addresses the representativeness of physical test specimens used in validation experiments — specifically, whether the samples tested are drawn from the same manufacturing population as the device under assessment, accounting for lot-to-lot variability and material property variation. In this assessment, validation is performed against the FDA generic centrifugal pump benchmark dataset, which uses a standardized reference geometry rather than production device samples. The FDA benchmark pump is a defined reference artifact, not a sampled production device, and therefore the statistical representativeness of a sample population is not applicable. The relevant sample representativeness concern is addressed instead under the 'Relevance of the validation activities to the COU' factor, which documents the geometric similarity between the benchmark and the CPB device under assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor is intended to assess whether the input parameters used in the computational model are equivalent to those used in the physical validation experiments — a concern that arises when the model and experiment use different but nominally equivalent parameter sets (e.g., scaled geometry, surrogate materials, or translated boundary conditions). In this assessment, the CFD model boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity) are directly set to match the experimental test conditions within ±2%, with no parameter translation, scaling, or surrogate substitution required. Because the computational inputs and experimental inputs are identical in kind and directly measured rather than transformed equivalents, there is no equivalency gap to assess. The direct correspondence between model inputs and test conditions is documented under the 'Test conditions' and 'Model inputs' factors, which together provide the necessary evidence of input fidelity without requiring a separate equivalency assessment."
    }
